      <table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
        <tr bgcolor="#FFFFFF"> 
          <td width="16" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">&nbsp;</td>
          <td class="NewsTitle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><br>
            Whats up with the poll about event restrictions?&nbsp;&nbsp; <span class="NewsUser">Errol 
            - 24-09-2000 at 12:36:38</span> 
            <br>
		  <span class="NewsTitleDescription">The results from the poll <i>Should we impose restrictions on who and how many can attend an event?</i> are in:</span>
		  </td>
          <td width="16" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">&nbsp;</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
        <tr bgcolor="#FFFFFF"> 
          <td width="32" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">&nbsp;</td>
          <td class="NewsText" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
            <br>
			This poll was posted after the Council evaluated the Mistmoore event a weekend ago.<br><br>Almost 30 participants (25 Aegisians or so) joined in this and much fun was had. But, the sheer number of people made it very hard for the Event Master to coordinate the efforts.<br><br>The Council discussed the need for setting certain requirements or restrictions on the number of players and the level of these, when we created new events.<br><br>There are definite pro's and con's to both approaches (free for all or restricted).<br><br><b>Restrictions imposed:</b><br><br>This would mean that the Event Master was allowed to set a certain max. or minimum level on the participants and a max. or minimum on the number he felt the Event could sustain.<br><br>Now, events are meant to be fun and death are usually an integral part of any forage into a dangerous zone, but in order to try to keep the dying to a minimum and make the whole event more cohesive, the event master could set certain requirements on the participating members.<br><br>This would make sure that things wouldn't get out of hands and people wouldn't get bored out of sheer inactivity.<br><br><b>Free for all:</b><br><br>Free for all means that the event is just that. Free for all. All levels and no limit on the number of participants. Everyone can join if they feel like it.<br><br>This makes it truly challenging for the Event Master, since the zone needs to support a wide range of levels and the possibility of inactivity is large. Also the grouping can be difficult, since so many different level ranges are present. <br><br>But, all members can meet each other and have fun together, which is basically what this game is all about.<br><br><b>Summary:</b><br><br><i>I have decided, that it is by the Event Masters discretion, whether level requirements or a max. no. of players should be imposed on any given event.<br><br>The reason for this is simple:<br><br>Different events has different goals. Some are for sheer roleplaying, some for gaining specific items, some are simply to meet and have fun. I would love to always have free for all events, but it is simply not possible for the Event Master to allow this if we're talking about a forage into a very dangerous zone!<br><br>Preparation by both Event Masters and members participating in the event is essential. And setting all events to be "Free for all" simply isn't a valid option in my oppinion, if fun is to be had by all.</i><br><br><b>Then what?</b><br><br>What will happen is this. <br><br>All Events shall from now on be much more concise in their description. All events in the Events section should contain a recommended number and level range, so that players have a rough idea of the challenges involved.<br><br>Also links to maps will be included in the description and a loot list will be included.<br><br>But, all this is solely done on the Event Masters discretion. Do NOT expect all events to feature all of this. The Event Master just might feel it ruins the particular purpose of his or hers event. These are merely meant as guidelines.<br><br><b>Sign up:</b><br><br>All members MUST sign up prior to the event, so the Event Master can figure out grouping AHEAD of the actual event. This cuts down waiting time drastically. It also means that members must show discipline and sign up. We all know RL sometimes interferes, but do yourself and the hardworking Event Master a favor and sign up.<br><br><b>Get a map:</b><br><br>All members should print our maps of the zone where the event is to be held. This is simply to avoid people being completely lost. Although it certainly could add to roleplaying, it simply speeds things up when everyone do a bit of research before they start.<br><br><b>Be there on time:</b><br><br>All members should be at the zone of the Event well ahead of schedule if at ALL possible. No crying for ports 5 minutes before the event starts! This puts a terrible strain on the Wizards and Druids and is simply bad form. Again we all know the time restraints we all have, but make an effort ;-).<br><br><b>But, what about the results of the poll</b><br><br>The results are as follows:<br><br><b>Yes - 12 votes or 35 %<br><br>No - 22 votes or 65 %<br><br>Don't care - 0 votes or 0 %</b><br><br>This is an extremely positive result, since it clearly states that our guild focus more on the socializing aspect and not so much on getting clear-cut results from events.<br><br>Still, my decision stands and events are able to set requirements based on the Event Masters discretion. This might sound like I am going in the complete opposite direction of popular oppinion, but I have every confidence that this is the only way to make sure that we get the most out of our events.<br><br>Hail Aegis Lux.<br><br>- Errol
          </td>
          <td width="16" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">&nbsp;</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
        <tr bgcolor="#FFFFFF"> 
